It is the responsibility of the owner or manager of the group feeding establishment to ensure that personnel working in their establishment have been trained in food hygiene, internal procedures according to a training program, with their respective records and evaluations, as well as provide the necessary work instructions to ensure hygiene during operation activities.
* Hygienic handling conditions a. Reception or Direct Purchase.
During the reception or direct purchase of food, the following conditions must be complied with:
* Be carried out in clean, illuminated areas, free of disused materials, and protected from sources of contamination;
* During the process of receiving or direct purchase, the personnel in charge must inspect the food and verify the following:
* * During the process of reception or direct purchase, the personnel in charge must inspect the food and verify the following: That the food is maintained in optimal environmental conditions and temperature suitable for the conservation and freshness of the same;
* * That the food is in suitable conditions for consumption, free of pests and deterioration;
* * That the containers and recipients are intact, are made of material suitable for containing food and are used exclusively for this purpose;
* * That the processed foods to be used must be clearly identified, have their respective health notification and be within the period of useful life;
* * The owner or manager of the establishment shall have a register of suppliers with the information of the establishment.
* Storage.
Food storage should comply with the following conditions:
1. Storage areas should be located in a place exclusively for this purpose and in optimal clean conditions, avoiding exposure to sources of contamination;
* According to the type of product, environmental and temperature conditions must be guaranteed to be suitable for preservation and freshness, which will minimize deterioration and contamination of the food;
* During storage activities, the PEPS principle (first in, first out) or PCPS (near expiry, first out) should be applied depending on the nature of the product;
* In storage areas, food should be separated from the floor, walls and ceiling in such a way as to avoid contamination, on clean and well-maintained surfaces;
* The layout of food in storage areas should allow easy access by authorized personnel;
* Food should be placed in a manner that allows air circulation so that overcrowding of stored products is avoided;
* Food should be stored in a manner that prevents cross-contamination, preferably in closed or hermetically sealed containers that are separate and identified according to their nature;

