Child diets are described using the World Health Organization recommended infant and young child feeding (IYCF) indicators, which are widely accepted and used to capture optimal feeding practices in populations (WHO, 2010).
Here we focus on indicators related to adequate consumption of high quality complementary foods that are dense in key micro and macronutrients.
We assess this using the protocols recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO, 2008).
The DHS-2016 survey asked mothers a series of yes/no questions about foods consumed in the past 24 hours by children 6-23 months.
These responses were grouped into the following categories:
* Grains, roots, and tubers (e.g., barley, enset, maize, teff, and wheat);
* Legumes and nuts (e.g. chickpea, beans, groundnut);
* Dairy products (milk, yogurt, cheese);
* Flesh foods (meat, poultry, and fish products);
* Eggs;
* Vitamin A-rich fruits and vegetables (e.g. mango, pumpkin, carrots);
* Other fruits and vegetables (e.g. onions, tomatoes, bananas).
This yields a count ranging in value from zero to seven.
WHO (2008) recommends that children in this age range consume daily at least from four food groups out of the above seven food groups.
This number was selected to maximize the likelihood that in addition to the staple food (grain, root, tuber), the child consumed animal-source foods as well as fruits and vegetables in the previous day (WHO, 2008).
This relatively simple indicator is highly correlated with more detailed measures of food intake (Ruel, 2003) as well as with children's micronutrient intakes4.
Moreover, several studies show strong correlations with this dietary diversity score and longer term measures of children’s
4 See Moursi et al. (2008); Daniels, Adair, Popkin, and Truong (2009), Kennedy, Pedro, Seghieri, Nantel, and Brouwer (2007) and Steyn, Nel, Nantel, Kennedy, and Labadarios (2006).
9 nutritional status (e.g.
child stunting prevalence) in a number of countries including Bangladesh, Ethiopia, India, and Zambia (Jones et al., 2014).

Extemporaneous preparation of medicated feed may be carried out under the authority of a pharmacist or a veterinarian mentioned in Article L. 5143-2, by a user approved for this purpose under conditions laid down by decree taken after notification of the National Agency for Food Safety, Environment and Labor.
Article L5143-4 Learn more about this article...
Edited by Order n ° 2011-673 of June 16, 2011 - art. 2
The veterinarian must prescribe, as a priority, a veterinary drug authorized for the animal of the species concerned and for the intended therapeutic indication or a medicated feed manufactured from an approved medicinal premix meeting the same conditions.
Where no appropriate veterinary medicinal product with a marketing authorization, temporary authorization of use or registration is available, the veterinarian may prescribe the following medicinal products:
1 ° A veterinary medicinal product authorized for animals of another species for the same therapeutic indication, or for animals of the same species for a different therapeutic indication or a medicated feed made from an approved medicinal premix meeting the same conditions ;
2 ° If the medicinal product mentioned in 1 ° does not exist, a veterinary medicinal product authorized for animals of another species for a different therapeutic indication or a medicated feed manufactured from an authorized medicinal premix meeting the same conditions;
3 ° If the drugs mentioned in 1 ° and 2 ° do not exist: 
(a) a medicine authorized for human use; 
(b) A veterinary medicinal product authorized in another Member State pursuant to Directive 2001/82 / EC of the European Parliament and of the Council establishing a Community Code relating to veterinary medicinal products, for the same species or for another species, for the concerned or for a different affection, without prejudice to the authorization mentioned in Article L. 5142-7 ;
4 ° In the absence of the medicines mentioned in 1 °, 2 ° and 3 °, a veterinary magistral preparation.
The medicines mentioned in 1 °, 2 °, 3 ° and 4 ° above are administered either by the veterinarian or, under the personal responsibility of the latter, by the holder of the animals, in accordance with the prescription of the veterinarian.

1 ° Group I comprises organisms, in particular microorganisms, genetically modified, meeting the following conditions: 
(a) The organism, in particular the recipient or parental micro-organism, is not liable to cause disease in man, animals or plants or to cause adverse effects on the environment; 
(b) The vector and the insert are of such a nature that they can not provide the organism, in particular the micro-organism, genetically modified with a phenotype likely to cause disease in humans, animals or animals.
plants or cause adverse effects on the environment; 
(c) The genetically modified organism, in particular the micro-organism, is not liable to cause disease in man, animals or plants or to cause adverse effects on the environment;
2 ° Group II includes biological agents that can cause disease in humans and constitute a danger to workers, or cause negative effects on the environment.
Their spread in the community is unlikely and there is usually effective prophylaxis or treatment;
3 ° Group III includes biological agents that can cause serious illness in humans and constitute a serious danger to workers, or cause negative effects on the environment.
TheirSpread in the community is possible, but there is usually effective prophylaxis or treatment;
4 ° Group IV includes biological agents which cause serious diseases in man and constitute a serious danger for the workers, or cause negative effects on the environment.
The risk of their spread in the community is high and there is generally no prophylaxis or effective treatment.
Article D532-3 Learn more about this article...
Created by Decree No. 2011-1177 of 23 September 2011 - art. 3
The classification, provided by the article L. 532-1 , contained uses of organisms, in particular micro-organisms, genetically modified into containment classes according to the group of the organism defined in Article D. 532-2 and characteristics of the operation, meets the following criteria:
1 ° Containment class 1 consists of operations involving genetically modified organisms in Group I and for which the risk to human health and the environment is nil or negligible;
2 ° Containment class 2 consists of operations involving genetically modified organisms in Group II and for which the risk to human health and the environment is low;
(3) Containment class 3 consists of operations involving genetically modified organisms in group III and for which the risk to human health and the environment is moderate;

# GB 2762-2022 National Food Safety Standard Limits of Contaminants in Food


## ., 

## national standards of People's Republic of China


## GB 2762—2022


## National Food Safety Standard Limits of Contaminants in Food


## 2023-06-30 Implementation


## National Health Commission of the People's Republic of China State Administration for Market Regulation

This standard replaces GB2762-2017 "National Food Safety Standard Limits of Contaminants in Food" and No. 1 Amendment.
Compared with GB2762-2017, the main changes of this standard are as follows:
--- Modified the terms and definitions;
--- Modify the application principles;
* ——Modified the limit requirements for lead in some foods;
* ——Modified the limit requirements for cadmium in some foods;
* ——Modified the limit requirements for arsenic in some foods;
* ——Modify the mercury limit requirements in some foods;
* ——Modify the words and positions of notes in Table 5;
* - Revise the limit requirements for benzo[a]pyrene in grains and their products;
* ——Modified the requirements for the limit of polychlorinated biphenyls in food;
* ——Modified the inspection method quoted for the limit of pollutants in packaged drinking water;
* ——Increased the conversion ratio of liquid formula for infants and young children;
* - Modified Appendix A.

## National Food Safety Standard Limits of Contaminants in Food

* 1 Scope
This standard stipulates that lead, cadmium, mercury, arsenic, tin, nickel, chromium, nitrite, nitrate, benzo[a]pyrene, N -dimethylnitrosamine, polychlorinated biphenyl, 3- Limit indicator for chloro-1,2-propanediol.
* 2 Terms and Definitions
* 3.1 Pollutants
Hazardous chemical substances that are unintentionally added to food produced during production (including crop planting, animal feeding, and veterinary medicine), processing, packaging, storage, transportation, sales, and consumption, or brought in by environmental pollution.
Pollutants specified in this standard refer to pollutants other than pesticide residues, veterinary drug residues, biological toxins and radioactive substances.
* 4.2 Edible parts

