These factors combined have put food and feed security at the centre of the EU's political priorities, and in a recent analysis on the driversof foodinflation, the Commission pointed tothe role of animal nutrition in achieving a sustainable and resilient agri-food system.
Feed legislation
Alongside the overall objectives of sustainability and security of supply, safety is a key legislative principle regulating the livestock sector in the EU.
Following the health concerns that arose in the early 2000s, most notably after the bovine spongiformencephalopathy (BSE, or 'madcow disease')
outbreak, Member States and EU institutions paid greater attention to sanitary controls in the livestock sector, resulting in extensive legislation to ensure the safety of animal products.
The relevant updated rulesinclude:2
* Regulation (EC) No 183/2005 laying down requirementsfor feed hygiene. Its subject matter includes the conditions and arrangements ensuring traceability of feed, and the conditions and arrangementsfor registrationand approval of establishments;
* Regulation (EC) No 178/2002 setting the general principles and requirementsof food law, establishing the European Food Safety Authority, andlaying downproceduresin matters of food safety that apply to all stages of production, processing and distribution of food and feed;
* Regulation (EC) No 1831/2003 on additives for use in animal nutrition;
* Regulation (EC) No 767/2009 on the placing on the market and use of feed. This regulation applies to both food-producing and non-food producing animals, and includes requirementsfor labelling, packagingand presentation;
* Regulation (EC) No 1069/2009 laying down health rules as regards animal by-products and derived productsnot intendedfor human consumption. Thislaw aims to prevent and minimise risks to public and animal healthand, in particular, protect the safetyof the food and feed chain;
* Regulation (EC) No 1829/2003 on genetically modified food and feed;
* Regulation (EU) 2017/625 on official controls andotherofficial activities performed to ensure the application of food and feed law, rules on animal health andwelfare, plant health and plant protection products;
* Regulation (EU) 2017/1017 on the catalogue of feed materials, a voluntary list for feed business operators;

* The food produced on the farms must be subjected to procedures that reduce the minimum of contamination and that prevent the inclusion of inappropriate components;
* Request, if necessary, the technical assistance of experts, to ensure nutritional levels that favor animal health, growth, production and welfare;
* Ensure that dietary changes are, as far as possible, gradual and nutritious and that acceptable food standards are adjusted;
* Prevent animals from accessing food and chemical storage places;
* Ensure that additives are not used in food for animals, to accelerate their growth, except in cases of duly proven recommendation;
* Do not use antibiotics without a prescription from the veterinarian;
* Do not use proteins from rumors to feed them;
* Use pastures by grazing density and in rotation, whenever necessary, in order to keep livestock healthy and productive and reduce parasitic loads;
* Record the rotation of pastures and the movement of animals from the farm to the corrals, stables, etc;
* Regularly inspect, clean and disinfect animal feeders and waterers;
* Ensure that the evacuation of effluents does not contaminate drinking water sources;
* Use herbicides and pesticides in a rational manner, respecting manufacturers' instructions and legislation
in force, as well as registering the products used, the date and the place of its application;
* Follow the manufacturer's instructions whenever food additives are used, as well as record the products used and the date of their application.
ARTICLE 14
(Environment and infrastructure)
Livestock breeders and managers must:
* Ensure that the construction of the animals' confinement sites corresponds to their needs in terms of living space, ventilation, drainage and manure removal. Soils must be flat and not hilly, and all surfaces are washable;
* Install the farms in areas free from industrial contamination and sources of contamination and infection;
* Ensure that the farm's buildings and fences are constructed in such a way that the risk of contact with animals on other farms and with wild animals is minimal;
* Confine animals in facilities at an appropriate distance from effluent disposal points;
* Ensure that beds are regularly renewed and safely disposed of after use;
* Apply pest control measures;
* Use disinfectants and cleaning chemicals in strict compliance with the manufacturer's instructions.
ARTICLE 15
(Handling of animals and products)
Livestock breeders and managers must:
* Ensure that all animals destined for slaughter are clean, healthy and in a condition to be transported, and have not been in contact with sick animals or infected materials;

