The proposed MRLs have been thoroughly assessed in accordance with international methodologies published by the OECD, VICH, or FAO.
Information on the technical assessment of each proposal is included in this document (refer section 3) and covers:
* the new or amended entry proposed for inclusion in the Notice;
* the rationale for the new entry or amendment being proposed;
* New Zealand good agricultural practice for the compound and target crop or species;
* the relevant residues information used in determining the proposed MRLs;
* a summary of the dietary risk and public health assessment; and
* the MRLs set by Codex and other authorities that are relevant to the new or amended entry.
Where an existing entry is proposed for revision, new or revised entry content is listed in bold print, and content proposed for removal is identified by a strikethrough.
The MRL compliance and dietary risk assessment residue definitions are included in the residues information section of the proposal.
The HBGV used to compare to the NEDI calculation and determine the potential public health risk is included in the dietary risk and public health assessment section of the proposal.

## 2.2.1 Amendments to Schedule 1: Maximum Residue Levels for Agricultural Compounds

MPI proposes to make the following changes to Schedule 1 of the Notice:
* An amendment of the entry for carbendazim, to revise the residue definition;
* An amendment of the entry for cyromazine, to revise the residue definition and set new MRLs at 0.2 mg/kg for eggs, 0.05 mg/kg for poultry meat, 0.05 mg/kg for poultry offal, 0.3 mg/kg for sheep edible offal, 0.3 mg/kg for sheep fat, and 0.01 mg/kg for sheep milk;
* A new entry for fluoxapiprolin, to set MRLs at 0.09 mg/kg for tomatoes and 0.01(*) mg/kg for potatoes; and
* An amendment of the entry for fluralaner, to set new MRLs at 0.01(*) mg/kg in sheep fat, 0.01(*) mg/kg in sheep kidney, 0.01(*) mg/kg in sheep liver, and 0.005(*) mg/kg in sheep meat. Note: (*) indicates that the maximum residue level has been set at or about the limit of analytical quantification.
* Amendment to Schedule 2: Agricultural Chemicals for which No Maximum Residue Level Applies

Art. 4. The Minister of Health shall conduct the state policy with regard to: 
1. the safety, the protection of the health and the interests of the consumers in the production, distribution and placing on the market of bottled natural mineral, spring and table waters; 
2. prevent the spread ofinfections transmitted to humans through food and water; 
3. the health claims in the sense of art. 2 (2) (5) of Regulation (EC) (1924/2006 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 20 December 2006 on nutrition and health claims made on foods; 
4. the laboratories in the system of the Ministry of Health, in which analyzes, tests and diagnostics of elements of the agro-food chain are performed.
Art. 5.
The Minister of Economy shall implement the state policy regarding safety and quality in the production of alcoholic beverages, ethyl alcohol and distillates of agricultural origin.
Art. 6.
The Minister of Agriculture, Food and Forestry and the Minister of Health shall jointly pursue the state policy regarding: 
1. the safety and protection of the health and interests of the consumers during the production, processing and placing on the market of: 
(a) novel foods; 
(b) foods treated with ionizing radiation; 
(c) foods intended for infants and young children, foods for special medical purposes, substitutes for whole-day food intake to regulate body weight and foods containing vitamins, minerals and certain other substances; 
2. the provision of food information; 
3. food additives, enzymes and flavorings; 
4. contaminants in food; 
5. pesticide residues in food; 
6. the materials and the objects, intended for contact with food; 
7. the assessment of the risk for human or animal health; 
8. the national, approved or branch food standards; 
9. food supplements; 
10. foods intended for use in intense muscular load.

